Imagine you’re running a popular restaurant. One day, you decide to change your signature pasta recipe. If you simply swap it out on the menu without telling anyone, your regulars who loved the original version are going to be disappointed — or worse, their dinner is ruined.
In backend engineering, your API is that menu. The mobile apps, frontends, and third-party integrators relying on your API are your regulars. If you rename a database column or alter a JSON response structure without warning, their applications will instantly crash in production.
The traditional fix? URL versioning: changing /api/v1/users to /api/v2/users.
While simple on paper, URL versioning often forces you to duplicate routing files, clone entire controllers, and create a massive maintenance burden.
But what if you could evolve your API payloads cleanly without touching a single URL? Let’s build an enterprise-grade Header-Based Versioning System in Laravel that keeps your code DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) and your clients happy.
The Nuance: Headers vs. URLs
Before we write code, let’s address the elephant in the room: Why not just use URL versioning?
Header-based versioning shines brightest when:

• Only the response structure changes (e.g., renaming fields).

• The API endpoint stays identical.

• The underlying core business logic remains the same.
Architectural Balance: If your entire application workflow changes radically, if your authentication guard completely breaks, or if the feature behaves entirely differently, URL versioning (/api/v2/...) remains the right tool for the job. But for payload evolution? Headers win every time.
The Visual Blueprint
Instead of dividing your routes across separate directories, everything passes through a single endpoint. The request lifecycle handles the context dynamically:

• The Request: The client calls /api/users with an X-API-Version: v2 header.

• The Middleware: An interceptor validates the header string, rejects bad inputs, and stores the valid version.

• The Controller: A single controller fetches data from the database, completely decoupled from presentation variations.

• The Eloquent Resource: The data shaper inspects the version context and modifies the JSON shape right before delivery.
Step 1: The Global Version Memory Box (VersionContext)
We need a central service to hold onto the requested version string during the lifecycle of the HTTP request.
Note: PHP’s native version_compare() expects numbers like 1 or 2.0, not strings prefixed with a "v". We'll add a quick normalization helper to strip out the prefix safely.
Create a new file at app/Support/VersionContext.php:
namespace App\Support;class VersionContext
{
protected string $version = '1';
public function set(string $version): void
{
$this->version = $this->normalize($version);
}
public function get(): string
{
return $this->version;
}
public function isAtLeast(string $version): bool
{
return version_compare(
$this->version,
$this->normalize($version),
'>='
);
}
/**
* Strips any 'v' prefixes so version_compare works reliably (e.g., "v2" -> "2")
*/
protected function normalize(string $version): string
{
return ltrim(strtolower(trim($version)), 'v');
}
}
Register this service as a shared singleton inside app/Providers/AppServiceProvider.php so the runtime state stays uniform:
use App\Support\VersionContext;public function register(): void
{
$this->app->singleton(VersionContext::class, function () {
return new VersionContext();
});
}
Step 2: Validating the Inbound Header via Middleware
If a client sends an unsupported header string like X-API-Version: abc, your application shouldn't blindly accept it. We'll write a middleware that checks incoming requests against an allowed whitelist and throws a 400 Bad Request exception for unsupported version parameters.
Create a middleware at app/Http/Middleware/ParseApiVersion.php:
namespace App\Http\Middleware;use Closure;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use App\Support\VersionContext;
use Symfony\Component\HttpFoundation\Response;
class ParseApiVersion
{
protected array $supportedVersions = ['v1', 'v2'];
public function __construct(
protected VersionContext $versionContext
) {}
public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next): Response
{
$version = strtolower($request->header('X-API-Version', 'v1'));
if (! in_array($version, $this->supportedVersions, true)) {
abort(Response::HTTP_BAD_REQUEST, "The requested API version '{$version}' is not supported.");
}
$this->versionContext->set($version);
return $next($request);
}
}
Register this right into the framework API stack within bootstrap/app.php:
use App\Http\Middleware\ParseApiVersion;$middleware->api(prepend: [
ParseApiVersion::class,
]);
Step 3: Why Eloquent Resources are the Perfect Home
Why mutate the payload inside the Resource layer?
Laravel’s API Resources are explicitly designed to transform Eloquent models into JSON responses. Keeping versioning choices inside the resource layer allows your controllers to focus entirely on core business rules, ensuring your data presentation concerns remain cleanly isolated in one centralized place.
Imagine a major database change:

• In v1: You returned a combined name string and an auto-incrementing integer id.

• In v2: You split name into first_name and last_name, and updated id to a secure uuid.
Note: Laravel Resources do not support classic constructor injection gracefully out of the box. We intentionally call app(VersionContext::class) inside the mapping method to access our global service container.
Create your resource wrapper at app/Http/Resources/UserResource.php:
namespace App\Http\Resources;use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use App\Support\VersionContext;
use Illuminate\Http\Resources\Json\JsonResource;
class UserResource extends JsonResource
{
public function toArray(Request $request): array
{
// Accessing the context singleton from the service container explicitly
$versionContext = app(VersionContext::class);
// Core data elements shared identically by all versions
$payload = [
'email' => $this->email,
'status' => $this->status,
];
// Conditional transformation based on version context evaluation
if ($versionContext->isAtLeast('v2')) {
$payload['uuid'] = $this->uuid;
$payload['first_name'] = $this->first_name;
$payload['last_name'] = $this->last_name;
} else {
// Legacy V1 Fallback Support Layer
$payload['id'] = $this->id;
$payload['name'] = "{$this->first_name} {$this->last_name}";
}
return $payload;
}
}
Step 4: Visualizing the Structural Payloads
Here is the beauty of this implementation. A call to the exact same controller method generates completely different outputs depending on the header provided.
Case A: X-API-Version: v1
{
"id": 1,
"name": "John Doe",
"email": "john@example.com",
"status": "active"
}Case B: X-API-Version: v2
{
"uuid": "c04b38d2-4318-4b72-acde-49bc70b134d9",
"first_name": "John",
"last_name": "Doe",
"email": "john@example.com",
"status": "active"
}Step 5: Writing The Production-Ready Integration Tests
An API version architecture is only as robust as its test suite. Let’s write feature tests to ensure that changes don’t accidentally break historical consumer applications.
namespace Tests\Feature;use Tests\TestCase;
use App\Models\User;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Testing\RefreshDatabase;
class UserApiVersioningTest extends TestCase
{
use RefreshDatabase;
protected User $user;
protected function setUp(): void
{
parent::setUp();
$this->user = User::factory()->create([
'id' => 1,
'uuid' => 'c04b38d2-4318-4b72-acde-49bc70b134d9',
'first_name' => 'John',
'last_name' => 'Doe',
'email' => 'john@example.com',
'status' => 'active',
]);
}
public function test_it_returns_v1_payload_format_with_legacy_keys(): void
{
$response = $this->getJson('/api/users', ['X-API-Version' => 'v1']);
$response->assertStatus(200)
->assertJsonPath('0.id', 1)
->assertJsonPath('0.name', 'John Doe')
->assertJsonMissingPath('0.uuid')
->assertJsonMissingPath('0.first_name');
}
public function test_it_returns_v2_payload_format_with_modernized_keys(): void
{
$response = $this->getJson('/api/users', ['X-API-Version' => 'v2']);
$response->assertStatus(200)
->assertJsonPath('0.uuid', 'c04b38d2-4318-4b72-acde-49bc70b134d9')
->assertJsonPath('0.first_name', 'John')
->assertJsonPath('0.last_name', 'Doe')
->assertJsonMissingPath('0.id')
->assertJsonMissingPath('0.name');
}
public function test_it_returns_error_for_unsupported_api_version(): void
{
$response = $this->getJson('/api/users', ['X-API-Version' => 'v999']);
$response->assertStatus(400);
}
}
Smooth Deprecations: Retiring Old Code Without Friction
Every developer knows the pain of deleting old code. With URL-based versioning, deprecating a system version means deleting entire folders of routing parameters, configuration files, and multiple controllers — a high-risk recipe for regression bugs.
With this resource pattern, retiring legacy systems is incredibly safe. Imagine it’s 6 months later, and you are ready to formally retire version v1 out of production completely:

• Remove 'v1' from your middleware $supportedVersions whitelist.

• Clean out the legacy else block fallback inside UserResource.php:

return [
'email' => $this->email,
'status' => $this->status,
'uuid' => $this->uuid,
'first_name' => $this->first_name,
'last_name' => $this->last_name,
];No route maps were broken, no duplicate controller files were touched, and your application layout stays completely optimized. Try out this header-driven pattern on your next Laravel project, and watch your technical debt disappear!
Conclusion
Choosing how to version your API shouldn’t feel like choosing a hill to die on — it’s entirely about picking the right tool for the job.
URL versioning (/api/v2/users) will always have its place when an application undergoes massive structural shifts, workflow updates, or breaking authentication changes. However, using it for simple database structural tweaks or payload modifications is like using a sledgehammer to crack a nut. It leaves behind a messy trail of cloned routes, duplicate controllers, and unnecessary technical debt.
By leveraging HTTP Headers (X-API-Version) combined with a global VersionContext and dynamic Eloquent Resources, you pull the versioning responsibility out of your routing layer and move it exactly where it belongs: the presentation layer.
The Golden Takeaway:

• Controllers stay lean and focused purely on data and business logic.

• Routes stay unified without duplicate endpoint configurations.

• Eloquent Resources act as the smart final gatekeepers, dynamically transforming the data payload representation based on the runtime context.
This strategy gives your application true enterprise elasticity. Old mobile clients continue to function perfectly on v1, your modern frontend flies forward on v2, and when the time comes to deprecate the past, you can clean house by deleting a few lines of fallback code inside a single resource file instead of blowing up your routing files.
